6. Why does this work?

Always use a real '(' before using a '*'.

Store indices to preserve the order.

After traversal, every remaining '(' must be matched with a later '*'.


Each index is:

pushed once

popped once


So the solution is linear.


---

7. Java Code

class Solution {
    public boolean checkValidString(String s) {

        Stack<Integer> open = new Stack<>();
        Stack<Integer> star = new Stack<>();

        for (int i = 0; i < s.length(); i++) {

            char ch = s.charAt(i);

            if (ch == '(') {
                open.push(i);
            }
            else if (ch == '*') {
                star.push(i);
            }
            else {

                if (!open.isEmpty()) {
                    open.pop();
                }
                else if (!star.isEmpty()) {
                    star.pop();
                }
                else {
                    return false;
                }
            }
        }

        while (!open.isEmpty() && !star.isEmpty()) {

            if (open.peek() < star.peek()) {
                open.pop();
                star.pop();
            }
            else {
                return false;
            }
        }

        return open.isEmpty();
    }
}


---

8. Time Complexity

Each character is pushed and popped at most once.

Overall:

O(n)


---

9. Space Complexity

Two stacks may together store all characters.

O(n)


---

10. Important Interview Note

The key idea is to use two stacks of indices:

One for '('

One for '*'


When a ')' is encountered, always match it with a real '(' first. If none exists, use a '*'. After processing the string, match any remaining '(' with later '*' characters while ensuring the '*' appears after the '('.


---

11. One-line Note for Interviews

Use two stacks storing indices of '(' and '*'. Match ')' with '(' first, otherwise with '*'. Finally, match remaining '(' with later '*' while maintaining index order. 🚀
